INST-5. Implementation workflow and task governance

INST-5.1. Progress artefact scope
INST-5.1.1. Files under `progress/` — including `progress/TASKS` and all task logs — document implementation work only; they must not contain entries for instruction authoring or architecture decision work.
INST-5.1.2. The term "task" throughout the instruction set refers exclusively to implementation tasks tracked in `progress/TASKS`; instruction and architecture authoring activities are governed by their own respective workflow sections and are not tasks in this sense.
INST-5.1.3. Instruction changes are tracked through `instructions/HISTORY` and git commit history; architecture changes are tracked through `architecture/HISTORY` and git commit history.

INST-5.2. Task ownership and authorities
INST-5.2.1. Assign active implementation workers to maintain the task logs in `progress/` that correspond to the work they execute.
INST-5.2.2. Empower architects to create, restructure, or otherwise edit the contents of `progress/TASKS` whenever planning work is required.
INST-5.2.3. Restrict implementation workers to updating only the status markers of existing entries in `progress/TASKS` unless they have been explicitly assigned architecture responsibilities for the change.
INST-5.2.4. Refrain from editing `progress/` artefacts unless fulfilling one of the roles defined in INST-5.2.1 through INST-5.2.3.

INST-5.3. Task initiation discipline
INST-5.3.1. Do not begin any implementation task in a new session until the user explicitly authorises work to start; authorisation applies to the current session only and must be renewed at the start of each new session.
INST-5.3.2. A specific instruction that grants standing authorisation for a named class of actions overrides the per-session default for that scope.
INST-5.3.3. Architecture and instructor subtasks within a session that follow from already-authorised planning do not require repeated authorisation unless their instructions mandate explicit approval.
INST-5.3.4. After authorisation, select the most relevant open task from `progress/TASKS`, respecting dependencies and priority indications.
INST-5.3.5. Review every architecture decision before editing project files or running commands so execution remains aligned with the approved design.

INST-5.4. Unified task ledger
INST-5.4.1. Treat `progress/TASKS` as the authoritative record for every task, subtask, status, and note; do not maintain parallel dashboards such as `progress/STATUS.md`.
INST-5.4.2. Preserve the existing hierarchical tree inside `progress/TASKS`, keeping indentation that expresses parent/child relationships untouched when adding metadata.
INST-5.4.3. Prefix each task line with a status marker in square brackets (for example `[open]`, `[in-progress]`, `[done]`, `[canceled]`) followed by the task identifier, title, and architecture references.
INST-5.4.4. Add contextual details directly under the task line by inserting metadata lines that share the task's indentation plus two extra spaces and begin with labels such as `Context:`, `Owner:`, or `Blocker:`.
INST-5.4.5. Keep metadata sentences concise — single lines are preferred — and update or remove them alongside status changes so stale commentary does not linger.
INST-5.4.6. When migrating notes from any retired dashboards, copy their text into the appropriate metadata lines under the corresponding task before deleting the legacy artefact.
INST-5.4.7. Reference the enriched `progress/TASKS` entries from task logs instead of duplicating their notes, linking to the relevant task identifier and relying on the embedded metadata for summaries.
INST-5.4.8. When a task's context changes (for example blockers resolve or scope adjusts), update its metadata lines before editing the task log so both artefacts remain synchronised.

INST-5.5. Day-to-day working practices
INST-5.5.1. Store implementation outputs exclusively under `implementation/` unless another instruction specifies a different location.
INST-5.5.2. Pause work, document blockers in the task log, and alert the user if the task diverges from scope or encounters major issues.
INST-5.5.3. Place reusable helper scripts under `tools/` and update `tools/INDEX` with usage notes when creating or modifying helpers.

INST-5.6. Commit discipline
INST-5.6.1. Apply these commit requirements to every task and subtask tracked in `progress/TASKS` or mandated by instruction.
INST-5.6.2. Complete each task or subtask in isolation, stage all related changes immediately afterward, and create the commit before starting the next unit of work.
INST-5.6.3. After finishing a subtask, produce its commit before moving on — even when multiple tasks were requested — so work never bundles several subtasks into a single changeset.
INST-5.6.4. Restrict the staged files to those relevant to the completed task or subtask unless another instruction mandates additional files.
INST-5.6.5. Include every `progress/*.tasklog` update in the same commit that records the corresponding work.
INST-5.6.6. Record the resulting commit hash and message in the corresponding task log, document any missed commits in the log, and create corrective commits as soon as issues are discovered.
INST-5.6.7. Confirm `git status --short architecture/` reports no staged or unstaged changes before modifying files under `implementation/`, and stop work to notify the user if architecture updates need review or commitment first.
INST-5.6.8. Avoid appending task log entries solely to note that a commit occurred; rely on the commit history for that traceability.
INST-5.6.9. Begin every task-related commit message with the associated task or subtask reference (for example `TASK-6`) followed by any concise description needed; include architecture or instruction identifiers when required, and rely on the prefixes from INST-3.5 for commits outside task tracking.

INST-5.7. Plan edit approvals
INST-5.7.1. Require explicit user approval for `progress/TASKS` commits only when architects revise the plan in response to new or updated architecture decisions.
INST-5.7.2. Permit implementation workers to commit status-only updates to `progress/TASKS` without additional user approval once work authorisation has been granted.

INST-5.8. Verification and dependency discipline
INST-5.8.1. Before marking any task or subtask complete, confirm that every referenced architecture requirement is satisfied in the real execution environment, not only through mock implementations.
INST-5.8.2. If gaps remain, document them in the task log, leave the task in progress, and continue implementation until the production-ready behaviour is present.
INST-5.8.3. When introducing or updating dependencies that require additional setup (for example browser downloads, OS packages, or migrations), apply the change immediately to all relevant Dockerfiles, bootstrap scripts, and documentation.
INST-5.8.4. Avoid deferring those updates or waiting for user approval when they are necessary for the dependency to function.
INST-5.8.5. Refrain from prompting the user for approval on work already authorised by standing instructions; only interact when new guidance, proposals, or conflicts demand clarification.
INST-5.8.6. Where interaction is required, keep requests specific and reference the instruction that mandates user input.

INST-5.9. Implementation traceability
INST-5.9.1. When implementation fulfils an architecture decision, add a nearby comment or documentation note that cites the most specific decision identifier.
INST-5.9.2. Review and update decision references whenever related code changes to ensure the linkage remains accurate, removing references only after the underlying decision has been superseded or deprecated through documented instructions.

INST-5.10. Autonomous testing
INST-5.10.1. Run all relevant automated tests autonomously before reporting task completion, without relying on the user to execute them.
INST-5.10.2. When test failure diagnostics or reruns are necessary, perform the additional executions independently and summarise the findings for the user.
INST-5.10.3. Activate existing virtual environments, install dependencies, or provision tooling needed to execute the tests whenever feasible within standing permissions.
INST-5.10.4. Document any environment setup actions in the active task log so future maintainers understand prerequisite steps.
INST-5.10.5. Request that the user run tests only when automation is impossible after exhausting available setup options or when explicit user interaction is required.
INST-5.10.6. When escalation is unavoidable, provide a concise summary of attempted remediation steps and the exact commands the user should execute.

INST-5.11. TODO tagging discipline
INST-5.11.1. When deferring any implementation work in code or configuration, add a `TODO` comment that cites the relevant task identifier(s) and architecture reference(s) motivating the follow-up (for example `# TODO(TASK-5, ARCH-1.6.2): implement real connector`).
INST-5.11.2. Place TODO markers immediately adjacent to the deferred logic so future contributors can locate outstanding items without scanning unrelated blocks.
INST-5.11.3. Mirror deferred work in the associated task log entry, referencing the same task and architecture identifiers to keep textual and in-code notes aligned.
INST-5.11.4. Remove or update TODO comments as soon as the underlying work is complete to prevent stale reminders from lingering in the codebase.

